For anyone who is unfamiliar with @ban__be , it is a Vietnamese American bakery located in the beautiful neighborhood of Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn.  Bạn Bè is recognized as the first Vietnamese American Bakery in New York City, and the baker and owner, @doris.hokane , is also the archivist behind @17.21women 

For everyone who is familiar with Bạn Bè, you know that it is also an epicenter for marginalized communities to come together, to slow down, to laugh, and to have meaningful conversations about how food, art, and representation matter. While most of us come for delicious Vietnamese baked goods and coffee, we return again and again because we love Doris, Mark and their precious kids (who are a big part of what makes Bạn Bè special). The whole family can be seen contributing to the bakery and warmth that welcomes you in.

Please know this is not a fundraiser where the family decided to reach out for help - they're much more comfortable giving to the community than asking for anything from the community. Instead, this fundraiser is from members of the community recognizing a moment of need and an opportunity to uphold our community values.

Last week, one of their kids had to be rushed to the emergency room, sending the family into a state of panic and despair. After a long wait, the family have been able to move into the ICU, where they hope for a speedy recovery and a return back to home.

While our number one concern is for the health and well-being of their child, we also know that Bạn Bè is a mostly family-run bakery that has unexpectedly closed at the busiest time of the year. That being said, we ask that if you've ever had one of their cookie tins, a Pandan Waffle, or Vietnamese iced coffee, or any other delicious item of theirs, that you might consider donating any amount to support Bạn Bè, Doris, Mark and their family while the bakery remains closed. For those who haven't had the pleasure of visiting the bakery or trying any of their goods, Bạn Bè will welcome you next time you come to Brooklyn. But they need our help.  Please consider spreading the word if a monetary donation is difficult to do.  Thank you 🙏❤️

JUDGE SPOTLIGHT: Humberto Leon & Carol Lim @humberto @carollim | Earlier this year when we were brainstorming fashion figures for our Judge Committee, this legendary duo landed at the top of our list. Humberto Leon and Carol Lim opened the conceptual retailer Opening Ceremony in NYC’s Soho in 2002, forever changing fashion—and downtown New York—as we knew it. Early fans of Opening Ceremony will remember how the brand, from the very beginning, felt like one big family—“family” being the artists, designers, musicians, filmmakers, friends, and friends-of-friends who were drawn to Carol and Humberto’s hyper-creative, fun-filled world of dance parties, rooftop barbeques, and even scavenger hunts—real ones—that made a playground of lower Manhattan. As Opening Ceremony’s fame and platform grew, they moved the fun to the global stage, producing high-level mashups like their iconic “fashion films,” their faux-furry Where the Wild Things Are capsule collection, and their unforgettable 2018 runway show staged at Disneyland. To this day, all are welcome in Humberto & Carol’s world, as long as you come with an open mind and a thirst for fun. We’re thrilled to bring this legacy to the first-ever Booktique Awards by having OC’s cofounders as judges. Welcome to *our* family, Carol and Humberto!
